ost. Luke </div><div class="t m857 x23 h4 y841 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">19:10. </div><div class="t m2b6 xab h4 y95d ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">3. </div><div class="t m41e x54 h4 y95d ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">All creation shares in redemption. </div><div class="t mae4 x23 h4 yd97 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Rom. 8:19-21. </div><div class="t m13b x58 h13 y860 ff1 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Key Words: </div><div class="t m7a0 x56 h13 yd7a ff1 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">1. </div><div class="t m3eb x22 h13 yd7a ff1 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Love. </div><div class="t m247 x4f h4 yd7b ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">The original words of Scrip-</div><div class="t m197 x58 h4 y9bc ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">ture for the supreme benevolent emotion </div><div class="t m755 x58 h4 y157e ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">have the general idea of affection, including </div><div class="t m6e2 x58 h4 y934 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">the qualities of mercy, pity, friendship. </div><div class="t mec2 x56 h13 ye12 ff1 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">2. </div><div class="t m142a x22 h13 ye12 ff1 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Reconciliation. </div><div class="t m130d xbe h4 y203a ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">In the original the </div><div class="t m49d x58 h4 y7de ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">usual word for reconciliation in the Old </div><div class="t m595 x58 h4 yed1 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Testament carries the idea of &quot;to cover,&quot; </div><div class="t m12f8 x58 h4 y516 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;to atone.&quot; In the New Testament, two </div><div class="t m6a6 x58 h4 ye00 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Greek words translated </div><div class="t m454 xb6 h30 ye00 ff6 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">reconciliation </div><div class="t mf6 x195 h4 ye00 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">mean </div><div class="t m54e x58 h4 yfb3 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;to change thoroughly,&quot; &quot;to appease,&quot; &quot;to </div><div class="t m2ae x58 h4 yd45 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">be merciful to.&quot; </div><div class="t m2ca x56 h13 ydce ff1 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">3. </div><div class="t m6df x22 h13 ydce ff1 fs4 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Restitution. </div><div class="t ma02 xa1 h4 ycb4 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">Our word </div><div class="t m2ef xea h30 ycb4 ff6 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">restitution </div><div class="t m425 x58 h4 y103f ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">has interesting connotations in the origi-</div><div class="t m586 x1c h4 y188f ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">nals. In the Hebrew there are the ideas of </div><div class="t m345 x58 h4 ycb6 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;to exchange,&quot; &quot;to make whole,&quot; &quot;to com-</div><div class="t m333 x1c h4 yfbd ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">plete,&quot; &quot;to make alive,&quot; &quot;to give,&quot; &quot;to turn </div><div class="t m342 x1c h4 y1213 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">back.&quot; In the Greek we have the ideas of </div><div class="t ma75 x58 h4 y940 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">&quot;to give back,&quot; &quot;to place down again,&quot; &quot;to </div><div class="t m9ea x1c h4 y10a4 ff4 fs3 fc0 sc0 ls0 ws0">restore,&quot; &quot;to make thoroughly right.&quot; </div></div><div class="pi" data-data='{"ctm":[1.000000,0.000000,0.000000,1.000000,0.000000,0.000000]}'></div></div>
